As the representative of Hill Air Force Base and an active veteran community, improving servicemember housing has been a priority my entire time in Congress. I am proud to introduce the bipartisan Fair Housing for Disabled Veterans Act with my @WaysandMeansGOP colleagues to ensure that our servicemembers and their families are better able to access affordable housing when they return home. Our veterans are more than deserving of affordable housing—especially when they are injured while serving.

The Pentagon recently reported that nearly 26% of U.S. military personnel experienced food insecurity in 2023. No military member should have to choose between serving our country and providing food for their families. That’s why I’m supporting bipartisan, common-sense legislation that widens eligibility for Basic Needs Allowance for our lower-enlisted servicemembers and ensures that more young families can support themselves in the early stages of military life.

Governor Cox, Utah law enforcement, the FBI, and all our state and federal partners did a phenomenal job in identifying Charlie Kirk’s suspected killer. In the midst of tragedy, they worked tirelessly to pursue accountability. We are all grateful for their efforts and demonstration of Utah’s hardworking spirit. My team and I continue to pray for Charlie’s family and loved ones during this unthinkable time.

Today, we pause to remember the lives lost on September 11, 2001, and honor the brave first responders, law enforcement, and citizens who ran toward danger to protect their fellow New Yorkers. Their sacrifice reminds us of the courage and resilience that define the American spirit.
 
September 11 is a solemn reminder of the strength and hope that unites all Americans. May we carry that forward as we work to preserve the freedoms and values that bind us together.
Charlie’s passing is devastating. Above all, he was a father and a husband. My heart goes out to Erika, his children, and his whole family.

My team and I are tracking the tragic shooting at Utah Valley University and seeking more information as it’s made available. We are praying for Charlie Kirk, his family, the students, and all those impacted.

This is why I'm leading the FALCON Act alongside @RepJillTokuda and @RepRonnyJackson to require Air Force and Pentagon leadership to plan out where the U.S. could partner with key allies on aircraft sustainment and developing forward sustainment positions in the Pacific Theater. This will strengthen readiness, increase burden sharing with our allies for the costs of aircraft maintenance, and ultimately reduce costs for the American taxpayer. It will also highlight Hill Air Force Base’s leadership role, serving as the nation’s fighter depot center of excellence and managing a satellite depot facility in Japan.

The tyranny of distance in the Pacific is one of the greatest concerns I hear as the congressional representative of @HAFB. In the event of a conflict in the region, U.S. logistics and supply routes back to the continental U.S. would almost certainly be disrupted, putting the Air Force’s ability to send aircraft back home for depot-level repair and overhaul under severe threat.

More than 100 years after being wounded in World War I’s largest battle, Cache Valley native Private Alonzo Stanton has finally been recognized with a Purple Heart. I was honored to present the Purple Heart to the Stanton family on behalf of President Trump. While posthumously awarding a Purple Heart for World War I service is exceptionally rare, Private Stanton’s courage and sacrifice warranted nothing less, and this recognition will help ensure his sacrifice isn’t forgotten in history.

This weekend’s stealth operation to strike three Iranian nuclear enrichment facilities was a testament to the professionalism and technological superiority of our armed forces. It also charts a pathway for a more secure Middle East long term.

The Trump administration’s decision to act now was time sensitive and for one fundamental purpose: preventing the Iranian regime from acquiring a nuclear weapon. I really want to emphasize the importance of timing here. Iran’s main nuclear facility at Natanz was enriching uranium past 60%, just a few short steps away from weapons-grade quality and far beyond the levels necessary to build a civilian nuclear energy program. For decades, the international community had tried to place limits on Iranian enrichment levels but failed repeatedly. Even the Trump administration made repeated efforts in weeks prior to bring Iran to the table, which were rebuffed.

The decision to destroy Natanz as well as the centrifuge cascades at Fordow and technology labs at Isfahan was the necessary one.

I’m also broadly supportive of the Commander in Chief having some discretion for making targeted strikes within the bounds of Congressional war powers. The 2001 Authorized Use of Military Force (AUMF) enables U.S. military operations against those responsible for the 9/11 attacks and those who harbored them. Iran fits this category well given that Al Qaeda and other terrorist groups have frequently been given safe haven inside Iran.

Remember, these laws are what enabled President Obama to take out Osama bin Laden in 2011, President Trump to strike IRGC Commander Qassam Soleimani in 2020, President Biden to take out Ayman al-Zawahiri (Bin Laden’s successor) in 2022, and now President Trump again for this strike. Democrats and liberal commentators suggesting that President Trump didn’t have the authority to make this call are not being accurate or credible, especially if they were unwilling to say the same thing about previous Democrat administrations. There are also a small number of lawmakers on both sides of the aisle who don’t think any President should have any war powers and have consistently voted against AUMFs. I disagree with their assessment, but I respect their opinion only if they are consistent regardless of party affiliation.

If the President came to Congress with these strike plans in advance, I am certain they would be leaked before the meeting was over. I would love to see Congress debate and vote on a new AUMF that accounts for modern threats and cleans up old language, but given current law, the Commander in Chief can legally take action. There is a clear majority of lawmakers from both sides that agree the President has limited authority in these situations.

I’m glad that these highly targeted strikes were conducted with zero American casualties or excess collateral damage. It opens up a pathway for a Middle East that is free from an Iranian nuclear threat, one that is more securely in the hands of our allies and partners. Our resources are not unlimited, so my hope is that this enables the United States to focus more attention on the Indo-Pacific moving forward.

The security environment in the Middle East is rapidly changing as we speak. I’m hesitant to offer definitive analysis in a time of such uncertainty, but here are a few core observations of mine from the past few days:
1) Israel’s clear-eyed decision to strike and dismantle a rogue Iranian nuclear program, one that was censured by UN authorities last week for breaching the Non-Proliferation Treaty, is firmly within the U.S. national interest. It’s a good thing that Iran’s ability to threaten the U.S., Israel, and our other allies with the nuclear weapon has now been degraded.

2) I’m glad that the White House has made clear that they are prioritizing the safety of our servicemembers in the region and the 500,000+ Americans living in Israel. They do not want to spark a wider regional war, and neither do I.

3) Conventional air superiority still reigns supreme. Drones/unmanned tech will continue to play a major role in the future of warfare but, as we saw, they cannot replace fifth generation aircraft. Utahns know this well with Hill Air Force Base being home to the nation’s first active duty F-35 wing. 

4) There is a quietly-growing consensus from our European and Arab partners that the best possible outcome is one where Iran can no longer possess a nuclear weapon. This consensus is long overdue.

5) Lastly, I realize this would be very difficult to achieve with the Ayotollah’s firm grip on power and the IRGC’s omnipresence, but I desperately hope this conflict leads to an opportunity for the amazing Iranian people to recapture a voice within their government and create more of their own destiny.

This bill is in direct response to what Americans have communicated they want—competitive tax rates, a more secure border, bolstered domestic energy resources, more support for our military, and less government waste. 

I worked to get on the Ways and Means and Budget committees for this very moment to represent Utah in this historic effort to lower taxes for hardworking families and support our small business owners. We’ve seized this opportunity head on, and now I urge the Senate to quickly move through the legislative process so we can get this bill to the president’s desk.

@WaysandMeansGOP 10. Delivers an additional $100 billion of investment over the next decade, making important enhancements for Opportunity Zones in rural distressed communities.

@WaysandMeansGOP 9. Deems the Sinai Peninsula and Sahel region as qualified hazardous duty areas for tax purposes. The Qualified Hazardous Duty Pay Area designation allows U.S. military servicemembers deployed in dangerous areas to be exempted from federal income taxes.

@WaysandMeansGOP 8. Allows tax-exempt distributions from 529 savings plans to be used for postsecondary education, including career training and credentialing expenses. This will help students and workers who choose nontraditional academic paths prepare for the workforce.

@WaysandMeansGOP 7. Creates a temporary deduction for non-itemizing taxpayers up to $150 for single filers ($300 for married filing jointly) for charitable cash contributions for tax years 2025 through 2028.
@WaysandMeansGOP 6. Increases the maximum amount a small business owner may expense under section 179 to $2.5 million.
@WaysandMeansGOP 5. Creates a new tax credit for individuals' charitable contributions to tax-exempt organizations that provide scholarships to elementary and secondary school students.

4. Creates Money Accounts for Growth and Advancement (MAGA) accounts to demonstrate to American youth the power of capitalism and compounding interest. Beginning on Jan. 1, 2026, parents of children under eight years old can open a MAGA investment account for their children. The government would seed accounts for newborns with a $1,000 federal deposit. These investment accounts would be eligible to receive contributions from family members, employers, nonprofits, and government entities, and will help set the next generation up for financial well-being.

3. Allows individuals who make less than $75,000 ($150,000 for families) to annually contribute an additional $4,300 ($8,550 for families) each year to their HSA, indexed for inflation. Additional amounts are phased out for individuals making $100,000 annually ($200,000 for families).
@WaysandMeansGOP 2. Makes the adoption tax credit partially refundable up to $5,000 (indexed for inflation) beginning in 2025.
@WaysandMeansGOP 1. Permanently increases the child tax credit from $1,000 to $2000, indexes the CTC to inflation, and provides an additional $500 for families through 2028.

At a time when terrorist activity in the Sahel is ramping up & Russian mercenaries are stalking the region to exert their influence, now is the time to provide this low-cost tax exclusion to uniformed Americans putting their lives on the line.

The QHDA designation allows servicemembers deployed in hazardous areas to exclude their compensation from federal taxes. Currently, only countries where servicemembers receive Imminent Danger Pay (IDP) are eligible for this designation. Mali, Chad, Kenya, & Burkina Faso have already been designated as IDP areas.

I joined a bipartisan group of lawmakers in introducing legislation to extend the Qualified Hazardous Duty Area (QHDA) designation to Mali, Burkina Faso, Kenya, & Chad, ensuring that U.S. servicemembers stationed in these high-risk areas receive critical tax exclusion benefits.
